# 26_scripter_singletons — substrate-layer suite for the Scripter
# window's singleton widgets (s206 m1).
#
# Substrate-style test (per TESTING.md grandfather clause). Each
# sub-test proves the substrate contract holds — abbrev resolves,
# verbs dispatch, queries read back.
#
# Self-referential. This script runs INSIDE the Scripter window
# whose widgets it tests. Several abbrevs would disrupt the test in
# flight if their click/set verbs fired mid-run:
#
#   - scr_clear / scr_copy : wipe or relabel the output buffer this
#                            test is writing to.
#   - scr_run              : reentrantly fires on_run_or_stop; the
#                            label is also live-tracked, so the
#                            script-read label IS "Stop" while the
#                            test is running, not "Run".
#   - scr_status           : opens a folder picker dialog.
#   - scr_save / scr_save_as : write to disk / open a file dialog.
#   - scr_step             : `set true` flips m_btn_step->get_active()
#                            to true, and the per-line step gate
#                            reads it on every subsequent line —
#                            mid-script flip parks the engine on a
#                            spacebar press (discovered in test
#                            26 v1).
#   - scr_hide             : safe to toggle (only read at Run start),
#                            but kept query-only for consistency
#                            with scr_step's posture.
#
# The test confines itself to substrate-addressability + state
# queries on the disruptive widgets, and exercises `set` round-trips
# only on scr_delay (which is read once at start_single_script time,
# so changing it mid-run doesn't reach back into the running engine).
# Click/set verbs on the disruptive widgets are deliberately not
# exercised — verb dispatch is already proven across the corpus for
# Button (tests 17, 19, 23) and CheckButton (tests 16, 23). The
# Scripter becomes scriptable from this milestone forward; future
# arcs that wire programmatic Run / Save / Save As coverage will
# exercise the click side then, from a controlling script run from
# outside the Scripter.
#
# Scope (s206 m1): nine singleton widgets value→pointer-flipped to
# substrate, plus one make_managed singleton flipped from raw
# Gtk::Button to substrate Button. Per-row sidebar widgets
# (row->check / label / del) remain raw — blocked on Reading C /
# model-object Scriptables (see LEDGER's Open Questions).
#
# The tested abbrevs:
#
#   Playback cluster (top toolbar)
#     scr_run        Run/Stop button (Button)
#     scr_step       Step-through CheckButton
#     scr_hide       Auto-hide CheckButton
#     scr_delay      Step-delay SpinButton (range 0..5000, digits 0)
#
#   Script tab content header
#     scr_save       Save button (Button)
#     scr_save_as    Save As… button (Button)
#
#   Output tab content header
#     scr_clear      Clear button (Button)
#     scr_copy       Copy button (Button)
#
#   Sidebar header
#     scr_lib_reload Library reload button (Button, icon-only)
#
#   Statusbar
#     scr_status     Change-folder button (Button, child Box w/ icon+label)
#
# DSL note (carried from s196 m1): the DSL lexer is kind-strict.
# SpinButton `value` queries return Double. Round-number literals
# in asserts against numeric queries must be written with explicit
# `.0` suffix (`assert ... value == 0.0`, not `== 0`).
#
# Test protocol:
#   1. Open the Scripter window (in a CURVZ_DIAGNOSTIC build it's the
#      second top-level window, opened from the diagnostic menu).
#   2. Load this script.
#   3. Run. Every line should PASS.
#
# Side effects: scr_delay is moved to 100 then 250 then restored to
# 5 (the launch default). scr_step and scr_hide are not touched.
# Net effect at end-of-run: only scr_delay has moved transiently
# and is restored.

#[sub] scr_run — Button. Substrate is honest about live state: by the
#[sub] time this assert runs, the Run handler has already fired (that's
#[sub] what's running this script), m_running is true, and
#[sub] update_run_button_label() has set the label to "Stop". The
#[sub] script-read label IS "Stop", not "Run". Same shape of evidence as
#[sub] s198 m1's zoom_spin baseline FAIL — substrate-is-honest-about-
#[sub] live-state pattern, third instance in the corpus.

assert scr_run label == "Stop"

#[sub] scr_step — CheckButton. Launch state is off (unchecked).
#[sub]
#[sub] No `set` round-trip here. `scr_step set true` flips
#[sub] m_btn_step->get_active() to true, and the per-line step gate at
#[sub] ScripterWindow.cpp:1280 reads that on every subsequent line — so
#[sub] a mid-script `set true` parks the running engine on a spacebar
#[sub] press, hanging the test. Same self-referential trap as clicking
#[sub] scr_run or scr_clear from inside the script. Addressability +
#[sub] label + initial-state queries are the substrate contract here;
#[sub] verb dispatch for CheckButton is proven elsewhere in the corpus
#[sub] (test 16, test 23).

assert scr_step active == false
assert scr_step label == "Step"

#[sub] scr_hide — CheckButton.
#[sub]
#[sub] Self-staged: write the state we want to assert, then assert it.
#[sub] The pre-s224 m1 test asserted `active == false` against the
#[sub] launch default, but the user can toggle Auto-hide between
#[sub] runs (it's exactly the kind of session-persistent control that
#[sub] survives a Run), so the launch-state-only assert was fragile
#[sub] to session history. Same hazard category as the pre-s224 m1
#[sub] scr_copy drift — state coupling to session history. The fix
#[sub] here is to actively stage the state before reading.
#[sub]
#[sub] Toggling Auto-hide mid-run is safe (unlike scr_step): the read
#[sub] site at line 1130 is consulted only at Run start, so any
#[sub] mid-run flip wouldn't reach back into the running engine. We
#[sub] restore to false at the end so the test leaves the user's
#[sub] Auto-hide preference in a known clean state.
#[sub]
#[sub] s224 m1: abbrev renamed from scr_lower to scr_hide to match
#[sub] the s221 m1 Auto-hide repurposing. Asserted label is now
#[sub] "Auto-hide" (was "Auto-lower" pre-s221 m1, which the test
#[sub] still encoded until this milestone).

scr_hide set false
assert scr_hide active == false
scr_hide set true
assert scr_hide active == true
scr_hide set false
assert scr_hide active == false
assert scr_hide label == "Auto-hide"

#[sub] scr_delay — SpinButton. Range and launch value.

assert scr_delay min == 0.0
assert scr_delay max == 5000.0
assert scr_delay value == 5.0

#[sub] scr_delay — set/value round-trip. Move to 100, then to 250,
#[sub] then restore to the launch default of 5.

scr_delay set 100.0
assert scr_delay value == 100.0
scr_delay set 250.0
assert scr_delay value == 250.0
scr_delay set 5.0
assert scr_delay value == 5.0

#[sub] scr_save — Button. Label is "Save". (Visibility/sensitivity
#[sub] are derived from the loaded-and-dirty state of the editor; not
#[sub] asserted here because the test's load state isn't fixed.)

assert scr_save label == "Save"

#[sub] scr_save_as — Button. Label is "Save As…".

assert scr_save_as label == "Save As…"

#[sub] scr_clear — Button. Label is "Clear".

assert scr_clear label == "Clear"

#[sub] scr_copy — Button. Label is "Copy".
#[sub]
#[sub] s224 m1: previously this sub-test used `get scr_copy label`
#[sub] rather than `assert` because the s206 m1 milestone surfaced a
#[sub] latent label-drift quirk — build_ui set the label to "Copy" at
#[sub] construction, but on_copy_output's idle timer restored it to
#[sub] "Copy output" after the first click, so the asserted value
#[sub] would depend on whether Copy had been clicked in this Scripter
#[sub] session (e.g. to grab the previous test run's output). The
#[sub] drift is harmonised in s224 m1 (the post-click restore now
#[sub] sets "Copy" to match build_ui and the sibling Clear button), so
#[sub] this is now a stable assert. If a future change reopens the
#[sub] drift, this assert will catch it the next time test 26 runs
#[sub] after a Copy click.

assert scr_copy label == "Copy"

#[sub] scr_lib_reload — Button. Icon-only (set_icon_name without a
#[sub] set_label), so label query returns "" — same shape as the
#[sub] icon-only Buttons proved in test 17.

assert scr_lib_reload label == ""

#[sub] scr_status — Button. Icon-only at the button level too: the
#[sub] visible row is the child Box (folder icon + path label), set
#[sub] via set_child, not via the button's own label. Label query
#[sub] returns "" — same shape as scr_lib_reload above.

assert scr_status label == ""

#[sub] Done. 10 new substrate widgets, all addressable. The Scripter
#[sub] window now has zero raw widget sites on its singleton surface;
#[sub] only the per-row sidebar widgets (row->check / label / del)
#[sub] remain raw, blocked on the Reading C design call.
